Part 1: Data Collection¶

First, we will import some libraries and load the CDC data into a Pandas DataFrame. Some of the data included by the CDC isn't necessary for this analysis, so we remove it from our working DataFrame for simplicity. Note that this dataset has data for New York City and Puerto Rico in addition to all 50 states.

# reading csv
df = pd.read_csv('Conditions_Contributing_to_COVID-19_Deaths__by_State_and_Age__Provisional_2020-2023.csv')

# removing unecessary data
df = df[df['Group'] == 'By Month']
df = df[(df['Age Group'] != 'All Ages') & (df['Age Group'] != 'Not stated')]
df = df[df['Condition'] != 'COVID-19']     # our analysis is concerned with medical conditions which
                                           # contribute to death by COVID-19, so we don't care about
                                           # people who died without contributions.

# merging "year" and "month" into one column
df['Year'] += (df['Month'] - 1) / 12

# deleting unecessary columns
del df['Group']
del df['Start Date']
del df['End Date']
del df['Data As Of']
del df['Flag']
del df['ICD10_codes']
del df['Number of Mentions']
del df['Month']

# removing unusable data
df.dropna(axis='index', inplace=True)
df = df[df['State'] != 'United States']  # different measurement techniques by CDC make this data 
                                         # incompatible with state-specific data

Finally, we create a third DataFrame which contains state-specific data on COVID deaths. In this DataFrame, each row corresponds to the total number of COVID deaths associated with the given state, condition, and age group. We choose to eliminate the "year" column due to the inconsistent reporting timelines across states, as will be seen in the exploratory analysis. Instead, we will base our analysis on the total number of COVID deaths from 2020-2023.

Finally, we will normalize our data. To do this, we divide the number of COVID deaths in each row by the total number of COVID deaths associated with the year, state, and age group of that particular row. For the national dataframe, we will just normalize by year and age range. For the state-specific dataframe, we will normalize by state and age-group. This will result in us having the percentage of each condition's contribution to the total COVID deaths for every combination of the other columns.

Then, we will calculate the difference between each condition's percentage and the corresponding national average percentage for the general and state-specific datasets.

In [5]:
def normDeathsByCol(frame, col):
    # Adds a column to "frame" which represents the percent/100 of all covid deaths in
    # col(s) which are due to each row.
    
    new = pd.DataFrame()
    
    for tag, group in frame.groupby(col):
        total = group['COVID-19 Deaths'].sum()
        group['norm'] = group['COVID-19 Deaths'] / total if total != 0.0 else 0.0
        new = pd.concat([new, group])
    
    return new

def diffFromAvg(frame, total):
    # Adds a column to "frame" which represents the difference between the normalized deaths
    # of each row and the normalized deaths of the United States for that year,condition, and
    # age group.
    
    total = total.copy()
    total['diff'] = total['norm']
    frame = frame.merge(total, how='right', on=['Year', 'Condition Group', 'Condition', 'Age Group'])
    del frame['COVID-19 Deaths_y']
    del frame['norm_y']
    frame = frame.rename(columns={'COVID-19 Deaths_x':'COVID-19 Deaths', 'norm_x':'norm'})
    frame['diff'] = frame['norm'] - frame['diff']
    return frame

df = normDeathsByCol(df, ['Year', 'State', 'Age Group'])
natltotal = normDeathsByCol(natltotal, ['Year', 'Age Group'])
statetotal = normDeathsByCol(statetotal, ['State', 'Age Group'])
df = diffFromAvg(df, natltotal)
df.head()

Part 2: Exploratory Analysis¶

Now that our primary dataframes are prepared, we can do some exploratory data analysis using the matplotlib and seaborn libraries.

First, let's look at the time evolution of condition prevalences among COVID deaths for different age groups.

Due to differences in data reporting timelines from state to state, the raw data is often "jumpy" from month to month. To visually correct for this "jumpiness" in the plots, we will plot the 6-month rolling average for each condition.

Note: deaths exclusively related to COVID-19 (i.e. no contributing conditons) are excluded from these plots due to their much higher prevalence.

In [42]:
rolling_avg_size = 6    # number of months included in the rolling average

for age, d1 in natltotal.groupby('Age Group'):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))
    plt.title(f'Contributing Condition Prevalence over Time for Ages {age}')
    plt.xlabel('Year')
    plt.ylabel('Percent of All Deaths (1.0 = 100%)')
    
    for cnd, d2 in d1.groupby('Condition Group'):
        if cnd in ['COVID-19']:
            continue
        
        plt.plot(d2['Year'], d2['norm'].rolling(rolling_avg_size).mean(), label=f'{cnd}')
    
    plt.legend(prop={'size':7})
    plt.grid(linestyle='--')
    plt.show()

As we can see, various health conditions become increasingly associated with death due to COVID-19 in older age groups.

Next, we will look at the state-specific normalized deviations from the national averages for various conditions, which we previously calculated.

In [9]:
for cnd, d1 in df.groupby('Condition Group'):
    if cnd in ['All other conditions and causes (residual)', 'COVID-19']:
        continue
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))
    plt.title(cnd)
    data = pd.DataFrame(columns=['State', 'diff'])
    
    for state, d2 in d1.groupby('State'):
        if state == 'United States':
            continue
        new = pd.DataFrame({'State': [state], 'diff': [d2['diff'].mean()]})
        data = pd.concat([data, new], ignore_index=True)

    bar = sns.barplot(data=data, x='State', y='diff')
    bar.set_xticklabels(bar.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45, ha="right")
    plt.gca().yaxis.grid(False)
    plt.gca().xaxis.grid(True)
    
    plt.show()

These bar plots give lots of useful information about the relative strengths and weaknesses of each state's response to the pandemic.

To better visualise this information, lets draw a map of the US, and label each state with its deadliest condition (relative to the average).

The simplest way to do this is by creating a new DataFrame:

In [29]:
unique = df['State'].unique()
max_diff = pd.DataFrame(index=unique, columns=['Condition Group', 'Condition', 'diff'])
max_diff['diff'] = np.ones([len(unique), 1]) * -np.inf

for tag, data in statetotal.groupby(['State', 'Condition Group', 'Condition']):
    state, cg, c = tag
    mean_diff = data['diff'].mean()
    
    if max_diff.loc[state]['diff'] < mean_diff:
        max_diff.loc[state, 'Condition Group'] = cg
        max_diff.loc[state, 'Condition'] = c
        max_diff.loc[state, 'diff'] = mean_diff

max_diff['State'] = max_diff.index.map(ABBREV)
max_diff.head()
